│ the Issue\n\nThe crash is an assertion failure, `OpIdx <     │
│ Operands.size()`, within `BoUpSLP::TreeEntry::getOperand`.   │
│ This means we're trying to access an operand of a            │
│ `TreeEntry` that doesn't exist. A `TreeEntry` represents a   │
│ node in the SLP vectorization tree, which corresponds to a   │
│ group of scalar instructions that we're trying to vectorize. │
│ The `Operands` field of a `TreeEntry` stores the vectorized  │
│ operands for the instruction group.\n\nThe assertion failure │
│ indicates a mismatch between the number of operands the code │
│ *thinks* the `TreeEntry` should have and the number of       │
│ operand groups it actually has.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s  │
│ Log and Backtrace\n\nThe backtrace is key here. The crash    │
│ occurs deep within the cost analysis for a horizontal        │
│ reduction:\n\n`vectorizeCmpInsts` ->                         │
│ `vectorizeRootInstruction` -> `vectorizeHorReduction` ->     │
│ `tryToReduce` -> `getTreeCost` -> `getEntryCost` ->          │
│ `getOperand`\n\nThis tells us that the vectorizer has        │
│ identified a potential horizontal reduction and is building  │
│ an SLP tree to model and cost it. The `tryToReduce` function │
│ in the `HorizontalReduction` class is where the `BoUpSLP`    │
│ object is constructed and the tree is built. The crash       │
│ happens when we try to calculate the cost of this            │
│ tree.\n\nThe `opt` log shows the vectorizer successfully     │
│ building and scheduling several groups of instructions. The  │
│ crash happens during the cost calculation phase              │
│ (`Calculating cost for tree of size 12...`), which suggests  │
│ the tree itself was built incorrectly.\n\n### 3. Root Cause  │
│ Analysis\n\nThe root of the problem lies in how the SLP tree │
│ is constructed for this specific horizontal reduction. The   │
│ `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` function attempts to      │
│ build a vector from a chain of associative operations (in    │
│ this case, a chain of `and` instructions).\n\nThe logic in   │
│ `tryToReduce` builds the SLP tree by creating `TreeEntry`    │
│ nodes. A `TreeEntry` for a binary operation like `and`       │
│ should have two operand groups. However, in this specific    │
│ case, a `TreeEntry` is being created with only *one* operand │
│ group.\n\nLet's trace the logic:\n1.  `tryToReduce`          │
│ identifies the chain of `and` instructions culminating in    │
│ `%and.25.i358.i.i`.\n2.  It iterates through this chain,     │
│ creating `TreeEntry` nodes for each level of the             │
│ reduction.\n3.  The function `BoUpSLP::buildTree` is called  │
│ to construct these nodes.\n4.  A crucial part of `buildTree` │
│ is to gather the operands for the new `TreeEntry`. It        │
│ iterates through the scalar instructions in the entry and    │
│ collects their operands.\n5.  The issue is that for the      │
│ final `and` in the chain (`%and.25.i358.i.i`), one of its    │
│ operands (`%and.24.i351.i.i`) is also part of the reduction  │
│ chain and is therefore considered an \"internal\" value. The │
│ logic incorrectly filters out this internal operand, leading │
│ to the creation of a `TreeEntry` for the `and` instruction   │
│ with only its *other* operand (`%c25.i357.i.i`).\n6.  Later, │
│ when `getEntryCost` is called on this malformed `TreeEntry`, │
│ it queries the number of operands from the first scalar      │
│ instruction (`and` has 2 operands). It then tries to access  │
│ the second operand group (`OpIdx = 1`), which was never      │
│ created, leading to the out-of-bounds assertion.\n\nThe      │
│ specific flaw is in `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`. It   │
│ adds the root of the reduction chain to a `SmallPtrSet`      │
│ called `ReduxChain`. When `BoUpSLP::buildTree` is later      │
│ called, it uses this set to identify and exclude             │
│ \"internal\" nodes from the operand list. However, it        │
│ shouldn't exclude the immediate operand of the root of the   │
│ sub-tree it's currently building.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit    │
│ Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to ensure that when building the SLP  │
│ tree for the horizontal reduction, we don't prematurely mark │
│ the operand of the current reduction step as internal to the │
│ whole chain. We should remove it from the `ReduxChain` set   │
│ just before building the tree for that level.\n\n```cpp\n//  │
│ In llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n\n// ... │
│ inside HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce ...\n    // Build    │
│ the tree from the bottom up.\n    for (Instruction *I : VL)  │
│ {\n      // The operand of the reduction is not part of the  │
│ chain.\n      ReduxChain.erase(I); // <-- This is the fix.\n │
│ V.buildTree(I);\n    }\n```\n\nThis change ensures that when │
│ `V.buildTree(I)` is called, the operand of `I` that is also  │
│ in the reduction chain is correctly identified as an         │
│ operand, not as an internal part of the tree to be ignored.  │
│ This results in a correctly formed `TreeEntry` with two      │
│ operand groups.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe bug is caused by │
│ an incorrectly constructed SLP tree for a horizontal         │
│ reduction, where an internal node of the reduction chain was │
│ improperly excluded from the operand list of a `TreeEntry`.  │
│ The proposed one-line fix corrects this by refining the set  │
│ of internal nodes at each step of the tree construction,     │
│ ensuring that `TreeEntry` nodes are created with the correct │
│ number of operands. This will prevent the assertion failure  │
│ during the cost analysis phase."})                           │
