│ `BoUpSLP::TreeEntry::getOperand`\n\nThis sequence indicates  │
│ that the SLP vectorizer has identified a chain of            │
│ associative instructions (a horizontal reduction, in this    │
│ case, a chain of `and` operations) and is attempting to      │
│ vectorize it. The `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`         │
│ function is responsible for building an SLP tree to model    │
│ this reduction and then calculating its vectorization cost.  │
│ The crash happens during this cost calculation               │
│ (`getTreeCost`), which strongly suggests that the SLP tree   │
│ itself was constructed incorrectly.\n\nThe `opt` debug log   │
│ shows the vectorizer identifying and building trees for      │
│ various instruction groups. The crash occurs after the log   │
│ message \"Calculating cost for tree of size 12.\", which     │
│ confirms the problem lies in the costing of a just-built     │
│ tree.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root cause is a   │
│ logic error in `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` that leads │
│ to the creation of a malformed `TreeEntry`.\n\n1.  The       │
│ function identifies a reduction chain (e.g., `R = A & B; S = │
│ R & C; T = S & D;`). It stores all instructions in this      │
│ chain (`R`, `S`, `T`) in a `SmallPtrSet` called              │
│ `ReduxChain`.\n2.  It then iterates through the instructions │
│ of the chain in reverse order (from `T` back to `R`) to      │
│ build the SLP tree from the bottom up. For each instruction  │
│ `I` in the chain, it calls `BoUpSLP::buildTree(I)`.\n3.  The │
│ `buildTree` function, when creating a `TreeEntry` for an     │
│ instruction, gathers its operands. It checks if an operand   │
│ is present in the `ReduxChain` set. If it is, the operand is │
│ considered \"internal\" to the reduction and is *not* added  │
│ as an explicit operand to the `TreeEntry`.\n4.  Here lies    │
│ the bug: When building the tree for instruction `I` (e.g.,   │
│ `T = S & D`), its operand `S` is still in `ReduxChain`. The  │
│ logic incorrectly treats `S` as an internal node that should │
│ be ignored, rather than as a direct operand for the          │
│ `TreeEntry` being built for `T`.\n5.  As a result, the       │
│ `TreeEntry` for the `and` instruction `T` is created with    │
│ only one operand group (for `D`), instead of the required    │
│ two (for `S` and `D`).\n6.  Later, when `getEntryCost` is    │
│ called, it inspects the scalar instruction `T` (an `and`),   │
│ sees it has two operands, and tries to access the second     │
│ operand group (`OpIdx = 1`) from the `TreeEntry`. Since this │
│ group was never created, the `Operands.size()` is 1, and the │
│ assertion `1 < 1` fails.\n\nThe fix is to ensure that when   │
│ building the tree for a specific instruction `I` in the      │
│ reduction chain, its direct operand that is also part of the │
│ chain is not considered \"internal\" *at that specific       │
│ step*. We can achieve this by temporarily removing `I`       │
│ itself from the `ReduxChain` set just before calling         │
│ `buildTree(I)`.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix  │
│ is to modify the loop in `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`  │
│ to remove the current instruction from the `ReduxChain` set  │
│ before building its corresponding `TreeEntry`. This ensures  │
│ its operands are correctly identified.\n\n**File**:          │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`\n**Edit**: │
│ Replace lines 18812-18814.\n\n**Original Code (lines         │
│ 18812-18814):**\n```cpp\n    for (Instruction *I : VL) {\n   │
│ V.buildTree(I);\n    }\n```\n\n**Proposed Code:**\n```cpp\n  │
│ for (Instruction *I : VL) {\n      // The operand of the     │
│ reduction is not part of the chain.\n                        │
│ ReduxChain.erase(I);\n      V.buildTree(I);\n                │
│ }\n```\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe crash is due to the       │
│ incorrect construction of an SLP tree for a horizontal       │
│ reduction, where an operand of a reduction step was          │
│ mistakenly classified as an internal node and omitted from   │
│ the `TreeEntry`'s operand list. By removing the current      │
│ instruction from the set of \"internal\" nodes before        │
│ building its `TreeEntry`, we ensure the tree is formed       │
│ correctly with the right number of operands, thus preventing │
│ the assertion failure in the subsequent cost analysis        │
│ phase."})                                                    │
