│ I have re-evaluated the problem. My previous attempts were   │
│ based on a misunderstanding of which values were being       │
│ processed. The `VL` in `tryToReduce` indeed contains the     │
│ leaves of the reduction, not the reduction operations        │
│ themselves. My attempts to modify the `IgnoreList` by        │
│ removing elements of `VL` were therefore ineffective.        │
│                                                              │
│ The root cause analysis is correct in principle: an          │
│ instruction in the reduction chain is being incorrectly      │
│ ignored during tree construction. This happens because the   │
│ `IgnoreList` contains all instructions from the reduction    │
│ chain. When `BoUpSLP::buildTree` is called, it recursively   │
│ explores the operands. If an operand is in the `IgnoreList`, │
│ the recursion stops for that path.                           │
│                                                              │
│ The problem arises when an instruction `I` in the reduction  │
│ chain has an operand `O` which is also in the reduction      │
│ chain. When building the tree for `I`, `O` is found in the   │
│ `IgnoreList`, and is thus treated as a leaf. This leads to   │
│ an improperly formed `TreeEntry` for `I`, which later causes │
│ the crash during cost analysis.                              │
│                                                              │
│ The correct fix is to ensure that when building the tree for │
│ a set of roots, the operands that are part of the reduction  │
│ chain are not prematurely pruned. The `IgnoreList` is        │
│ intended to stop the tree from growing beyond the reduction  │
│ chain, but it's too aggressive.                              │
│                                                              │
│ The analysis suggests removing the *current* instruction     │
│ from the ignore list. Since `tryToReduce` builds a tree for  │
│ a slice of leaves (`VL`) at a time, and the actual reduction │
│ ops are not explicitly part of this, the logic is more       │
│ complex. The `BoUpSLP` instance `V` is created inside a loop │
│ and doesn't have state about the whole reduction chain other │
│ than what's in `IgnoreList`.                                 │
│                                                              │
│ The most direct interpretation of the root cause is that the │
│ `IgnoreList` should not contain the instruction for which a  │
│ tree is currently being built. Since the tree building       │
│ starts from the leaves (`VL`), and walks up, the problematic │
│ instructions are the reduction ops themselves (the `and`s).  │
│                                                              │
│ The `IgnoreList` is constructed once at the beginning of     │
│ `tryToReduce` and contains all reduction ops. This is the    │
│ source of the problem.                                       │
│                                                              │
│ A correct fix should be to pass a modified ignore list to    │
│ `buildTree`. The `IgnoreList` should not contain the direct  │
│ users of the current leaves `VL`. However, identifying those │
│ is non-trivial.                                              │
│                                                              │
